# UDS Figma Preflight

Use this rule whenever a task interacts with either UDS Figma file, including
reading variables, inspecting components, importing tokens, syncing statuses, or
writing release notes.

## Canonical Figma files

| File | Key | Purpose |
| --- | --- | --- |
| UDS Tokens | `iqKgR73ubUHpQTIcF7XGMy` | Figma Variables source for primitive and semantic tokens |
| UDS Components | `1XJoUJgtNpw4R0IIT3VjoK` | Visual component source: component pages, variant sets, examples, status prefixes |

## Mandatory preflight output

Before doing any Figma-derived analysis or write, report:

```markdown
Figma preflight:
- Tokens file version: X.Y or unavailable
- Components file version: X.Y or unavailable
- Site UDS version: X.Y (from uds-docs/uds/version.json)
- Version mismatch: yes/no
- Figma capability check: pass/partial/fail
- Action: continue / dry-run only / pause for release flow
```

## Version detection

1. List pages in each relevant Figma file. Enumerate via the Plugin API
   (`figma.root.children` through `use_figma`), NOT `get_metadata` with
   no `nodeId` â€” the latter's top-level page list has been observed to
   under-report (it returned only the `UDS Version: 0.3` page for
   `UDS Components` while `figma.root.children` returned all ~55 pages).
   Treat a `get_metadata` page list as possibly partial and confirm via
   the Plugin API before concluding a page is missing.
2. Filter out any page whose name contains `{Ignore}`. Ignored pages are not
   part of UDS sync, inventory, release detection, component inspection,
   status sync, deletion detection, or new-component detection.
3. Find the page named `UDS Version: X.Y` among the non-ignored pages.
4. Parse `X.Y`.
5. Read the current UDS version from `uds-docs/uds/version.json` (the
   `version` field). The Next.js app reads this at boot via
   `lib/uds-data.ts`; the legacy vanilla `app.js` and its `UDS_VERSION`
   constant were deleted in the Next.js migration (Chunk 17).
6. If either Figma version is higher than the site version, pause normal work
   and follow `uds-release-workflow.mdc`.

Do not silently ignore a version mismatch.

## Ignored pages

Any Figma page with `{Ignore}` anywhere in the page name is outside the UDS
source of truth for automation. Treat it as intentionally hidden scratch,
archive, exploration, or non-system content.

Rules:

- Do not read ignored pages for token/component sync.
- Do not include ignored pages in page counts, new component detection,
  deletion detection, status sync, node-link matching, or release-note target
  selection.
- Do not flag ignored pages as "missing from docs" or "deleted from Figma".
- Do not inspect components inside ignored pages unless the user explicitly
  asks for that page by name and acknowledges it is ignored.
- If an ignored page looks like a duplicate of a live component, mention only
  that it was skipped; do not use it as evidence.

## Frozen pages (factory-maintenance opt-out)

A page whose name contains `{Frozen}` (or `{NoFactory}`) is a LIVE component
the designer has marked hands-off for the **component factory's maintenance
upgrades only**. Unlike `{Ignore}`, it is NOT removed from the system:

- It stays in inventory, status sync, new/deleted detection, release-note
  selection, and component inspection â€” it is a real, live component and is
  counted everywhere a normal live component is.
- The ONLY thing `{Frozen}` changes: the factory's maintenance mode and the
  `figma-inventory` factory-version drift pass still REPORT it as behind if it
  is, but propose and write NO upgrades to it. See
  `.cursor/rules/uds-figma-write-safety.mdc` scope #5 and
  `.cursor/rules/uds-factory-versioning.mdc`.
- Removing `{Frozen}` re-enrolls the component in factory maintenance.

The three page-name axes are independent: `{Cursor}` = permission (free
write), `{Ignore}` = visibility (hidden from automation), `{Frozen}` =
maintenance (factory proposes no upgrades). A page can carry any combination.

## Stoplight status mapping

Figma component page prefixes map to the `current` field in each per-component `uds/components/<id>/status.json`:

| Figma prefix | Status key | Badge label |
| --- | --- | --- |
| black / no started marker | `placeholder` | Not Started |
| red | `blocked` | Blocked |
| orange | `in-progress` | In Progress |
| yellow | `review` | In Review |
| green | `production` | Production Ready |

When the Figma prefix is ambiguous or unavailable, report `confidence: low` and
do not update the per-component `status.json`.

## Direct-read first

- Tokens: read Figma Variables directly first. Token ZIPs are fallback only.
- Components: inspect nodes/layers/variants directly. Screenshots are supporting
  evidence only.

If the Figma tool cannot read the needed structure, stop or fall back according
to the relevant rule. Do not guess from a screenshot.
